<div class="max-w-6xl mx-auto px-4 py-8">
    <h1 class="text-4xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-8 text-center">History of Embroidery</h1>
    
    <!-- Timeline Navigation -->
    <div class="timeline-nav mb-8 flex justify-center">
        <button class="timeline-nav-btn" data-year="3000BC">3000 BC</button>
        <button class="timeline-nav-btn" data-year="500AD">500 AD</button>
        <button class="timeline-nav-btn" data-year="1000">1000</button>
        <button class="timeline-nav-btn" data-year="1800">1800</button>
        <button class="timeline-nav-btn" data-year="2000">2000</button>
    </div>

    <!-- Timeline -->
    <div class="timeline">
        <!-- Ancient Egypt -->
        <div class="timeline-item" data-year="3000BC">
            <div class="timeline-content bg-white rounded-lg shadow-lg p-6">
                <img src="/images/history/ancient-egypt.svg" alt="Ancient Egyptian Embroidery" class="timeline-image">
                <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-800 mb-4">Ancient Egypt (c. 3000 BC)</h2>
                <p class="text-gray-600">
                    Some of the earliest evidence of embroidery comes from Ancient Egypt. Excavated tombs have revealed 
                    intricately embroidered clothing, accessories, and ceremonial pieces. The ancient Egyptians used 
                    linen as their primary fabric, embellishing it with threads of various colors.
                </p>
                <span class="timeline-date">3000 BC</span>
            </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Byzantine Era -->
        <div class="timeline-item" data-year="500AD">
            <div class="timeline-content bg-white rounded-lg shadow-lg p-6">
                <img src="/images/history/byzantine.svg" alt="Byzantine Embroidery" class="timeline-image">
                <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-800 mb-4">Byzantine Era (c. 500 AD)</h2>
                <p class="text-gray-600">
                    The Byzantine Empire elevated embroidery to new heights of luxury and sophistication. Gold thread 
                    and precious stones were commonly incorporated into ecclesiastical vestments and royal garments, 
                    creating stunning works of art that showcased both religious devotion and imperial power.
                </p>
                <span class="timeline-date">500 AD</span>
            </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Medieval Period -->
        <div class="timeline-item" data-year="1000">
            <div class="timeline-content bg-white rounded-lg shadow-lg p-6">
                <img src="/images/history/medieval.svg" alt="Medieval Embroidery" class="timeline-image">
                <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-800 mb-4">Medieval Period (c. 1000)</h2>
                <p class="text-gray-600">
                    The Middle Ages saw embroidery become a symbol of wealth and status. The famous Bayeux Tapestry, 
                    created in the 11th century, exemplifies the storytelling power of embroidery. Professional 
                    workshops and religious institutions produced elaborate pieces for both secular and sacred purposes.
                </p>
                <span class="timeline-date">1000</span>
            </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Industrial Revolution -->
        <div class="timeline-item" data-year="1800">
            <div class="timeline-content bg-white rounded-lg shadow-lg p-6">
                <img src="/images/history/industrial.svg" alt="Industrial Revolution Embroidery" class="timeline-image">
                <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-800 mb-4">Industrial Revolution (c. 1800)</h2>
                <p class="text-gray-600">
                    The invention of the sewing machine and mechanical embroidery revolutionized the craft. 
                    Josué Heilmann's embroidery machine (1828) and later innovations made embroidered goods more 
                    accessible to the general public while preserving the artistry of hand embroidery.
                </p>
                <span class="timeline-date">1800</span>
            </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Modern Era -->
        <div class="timeline-item" data-year="2000">
            <div class="timeline-content bg-white rounded-lg shadow-lg p-6">
                <img src="/images/history/modern.svg" alt="Modern Embroidery" class="timeline-image">
                <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-800 mb-4">Modern Era (c. 2000)</h2>
                <p class="text-gray-600">
                    Contemporary embroidery combines traditional techniques with modern technology. Digital embroidery 
                    machines, innovative materials, and computer-aided design have expanded the possibilities while 
                    artists continue to push boundaries with experimental approaches and mixed media.
                </p>
                <span class="timeline-date">2000</span>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</div>

<!-- Timeline CSS and JS -->
<link rel="stylesheet" href="/css/timeline.css">
<script src="/js/timeline.js"></script>
